{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647999"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18269"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18269"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,1,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10983"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7431"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of pain in her left knee following a fall during a netball game. She describes the pain as sharp and localised to the inner aspect of her knee. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness over a bony prominence on the inner side of her left knee, just above the joint line.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures is most likely to be the site of tenderness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Head of the fibula","Lateral epicondyle of the femur","Medial epicondyle of the femur","Patellar tendon","Tibial tuberosity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial epicondyle of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E is a bony prominence located on the inner side of the distal femur, just above the knee joint. It serves as an attachment site for the adductor magnus muscle and the medial collateral ligament. Tenderness in this area, especially following trauma, is consistent with injury or strain to these structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral epicondyle of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E is located on the outer side of the distal femur and is not typically associated with medial knee pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial tuberosity\u003C/strong\u003E is located on the anterior aspect of the tibia and is the attachment site for the patellar tendon. It is not associated with medial knee pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehead of the fibula\u003C/strong\u003E is located on the lateral side of the knee and is not relevant to medial knee pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epatellar tendon\u003C/strong\u003E connects the patella to the tibial tuberosity and is involved in anterior knee pain, not medial knee pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial epicondyle of the femur is a key anatomical landmark for the attachment of the adductor magnus muscle.","Understanding the anatomy of the femur is crucial for identifying sites of muscle attachment and potential injury."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18269"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:04:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T09:05:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10983"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}